value.value: A biologically active family of human endogenous retroviral elements that are found in human and primate genomes and resemble or are derived from retroviral genomic material. Aberrant expression of these elements may be associated with testicular germ cell tumors, breast cancer, type 1 diabetes mellitus, motor neuron disease.

label.value: HLA Class I Histocompatibility Antigen, A-0201 Alpha Chain

value.value: HLA class I histocompatibility antigen, A-0201 alpha chain (365 aa, ~41 kDa) is encoded by the human HLA-A gene. This protein plays a role in the presentation of foreign antigens to the immune system.

label.value: HLA Class I Histocompatibility Antigen, A-11 Alpha Chain

value.value: HLA class I histocompatibility antigen, A-11 alpha chain (365 aa, ~41 kDa) is encoded by the human HLA-A gene. This protein is involved in the presentation of foreign antigens to the immune system. Expression of this serotype may be associated with increased susceptibility to papillomavirus infection.
A protein encoded by the HLA-B gene.

label.value: HLA Class I Histocompatibility Antigen, B-44 Alpha Chain

value.value: HLA class I histocompatibility antigen, B-44 alpha chain (362 aa, ~40 kDa) is encoded by the human HLA-B gene. This protein plays a role in the presentation of foreign antigens to the immune system. Expression of this serotype may be associated with recurrent sinopulmonary infections and ankylosing spondylitis.
The posterior cerebral artery is formed by the bifurcation of the basilar artery; it divides into three branches.

HLA-DP4 antigen is a protein complex of the major histocompatibility complex, class II DP protein in which the alpha subunit is encoded by the HLA-DPA1*0103 allele and the beta subunit serotype is encoded by either the *0401 allele or the *0402 allele of the HLA-DPB1 gene. This antigen represents the most common haplotype.

HLA-DR13 antigen is a protein complex of the major histocompatibility complex, class II DR protein in which the alpha subunit encoded by the HLA-DRA*01 allele and the beta subunit serotype is encoded by certain alleles in the HLA-DRB1*13 group.
HPV major capsid protein L1 is encoded by the human papillomavirus L1 gene. This protein plays a role in viral capsid formation.
The antibodies produced by an individual that target the antigens (A or B or both) found on the red blood cells (RBC) of individuals with incompatible blood groups.
A protein encoded by the PGR gene.
Progesterone receptor isoform A (769 aa, ~82 kDa) is encoded by the human PGR gene. This protein plays a role in the regulation of gene transcription.
A protein encoded by the MSLN gene.
Megakaryocyte-potentiating factor (250 aa, ~27 kDa) is encoded by the human MSLN gene. This protein plays a role in megakaryocyte colony formation.
An aspartyl protease that is a portion of the polyprotein encoded by the gag gene found in the retrovirus myeloblastosis-associated virus (MAV; avian myeloblastosis virus).

A catenin protein with 10 armadillo repeats involved in the regulation of cell adhesion and tissue morphogenesis. Catenin delta-1 (CTNND1) is expressed in vascular endothelium, keratinocytes and melanocytes, and catenin delta-2 (CTNND2) is expressed in brain.
The terminal, cone-shaped end of the spinal cord.
The invasion of an organism's body tissues by disease-causing agents and their multiplication, as well as the reaction by the host to these organisms and/or toxins that the organisms produce.
An infectious disorder that occurs in childhood.
An abscess that develops in the space surrounding one or both palatine tonsils.
An abscess that develops in the soft tissues of the lateral pharyngeal space.
An abscess that develops in the soft tissues behind the posterior pharyngeal wall.
An abscess that develops in the tissues within the prevertebral fascia.
An abscess within the abdomen.
An abscess that is located in the anatomical space between the diaphragm and the liver and/or spleen.
An abscess that is located in any part of the tissue composing the mesentery, and that generally arises from an infection in an adjacent area of the intestine.
An abscess that is located in the anatomical space surrounding the liver, but which is outside of the liver capsule itself.
The artery that delivers blood to the anterior portion of the spinal cord.
An abscess that is located in the abdominal cavity posterior to the peritoneum.
An abscess that is located in the pelvic cavity.
A form of inflammatory arthritis that results as a reaction to a bacterial infection outside the joint.
A form of reactive arthritis in which the inflammation moves between joints.
Any disease caused by Legionella bacteria.
A self-limited, febrile illness without pneumonia that occurs in epidemics, and that is caused by Legionella species.

An infection that is caused by Burkholderia pseudomallei, which is found in soil and water; symptoms vary widely, but most commonly include fever, cough, pneumonia, arthralgia, myalgia, and skin ulceration.

An infection that is caused by Yersinia enterocolitica or Yersinia pseudotuberculosis, and that is usually acquired by consumption of contaminated meat, water, or unpasteurized milk. It can also be transmitted vertically, pre- or perinatally, from mother to infant. Manifestation of symptoms depends on the infecting species and mode of acquisition, and can range from gastrointestinal syndromes to septicemia.
Historical term that references a form of pneumonia caused by Mycoplasma pneumoniae, Chlamydophila pneumoniae, or Legionella species.

A pneumonia caused by Legionella pneumophila and other Legionella species, which is characterized by fever, cough, progressive respiratory distress, and which is often accompanied by extrapulmonary manifestations.

The rostral extensions of the ventricular system of the brain consisting of two cavities, one on each side of the brain within the central regions of each cerebral hemisphere.  Cerebrospinal fluid flows from the lateral ventricles into the centrally third ventricle via the foramen of Monroe.
An infection that is caused by Bartonella henselae, which occurs primarily in immunocompromised persons; it is characterized by blood-filled cysts in the liver and spleen.
Botulism that is caused by consuming food or beverage that contains the botulinum toxin.
Botulism that is caused by toxin that is produced in a wound contaminated with Clostridium botulinum.
Botulism that is caused by contact with spores of Clostridial bacteria, which subsequently grow in the intestine and release toxin.
A rare form of botulism that occurs among adults by the same mechanism as infant botulism.
Botulism that occurs following injection of botulinum toxin.

A transmissible, infectious disease that is caused by a protein that is able to induce abnormal folding of normal cellular proteins, leading to characteristic spongiform brain changes, which are associated with neuronal loss without an inflammatory response. Such disorders have typically long incubation periods, but are then generally rapidly progressive and are uniformly fatal.
Inflammation of the colon that is caused by an alteration in intestinal flora by antibiotic use.
The transmission of an infectious agent to a host's oral cavity via the fecal particles of another living organism.

A pruritic rash that occurs as consequence of cercariae penetration of the skin after aquatic exposure to animal (usually avian) schistosomes, often in countries non-endemic to human schistosomiasis. The condition is non-invasive and responsive to symptomatic treatment.

A very slender, longitudinal column of motor neurons in the ventrolateral medulla oblongata; its efferent fibres leave with the vagus and glossopharyngeal nerve and innervate the striated muscle fibres of the pharynx (including the musculus levator veli palatini) and the vocal cord muscles of the larynx.
